:"1237–1304","1268–1305":"1268–1305","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1275–1375":"1275–1375","1250–1301":"1250–1301","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","about 1270":"about 1270","ABT 1268":"about 1268","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Aft 1209":"after 1209","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","1237":"1237","1301":"1301","1268":"1268","1278":"1278","1332":"1332","1200":"1200","1375":"1375","about 1275":"about 1275","1209":"1209","Drymen, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Drymen, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Drummond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from any of various places, notably the barony of Drummond, which is probably identical with the parish of Drymen (Stirlingshire), named from Gaelic <i>drumainn</i>, a derivative of <i>druim</i> ‘ridge’. It has been said that the principal family of this name are descended from a Hungarian nobleman, Maurice, who accompanied Edgar Atheling and his sister Margaret to Scotland in 1068, where she married King Malcolm III. However, there is disagreement on whether or not this was the case.","English: occasionally perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Dromund</i> (Old Norse <i>Drómundr</i>, apparently from a word denoting a kind of Byzantine galley prevalent till the 12th cent., from Greek <i>dromōn</i> ‘runner’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Drummonds","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Drummond  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In Britain this surname is found mainly in County Durham."]}]},{"name":"Malcolm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval Gaelic name <i>Mael Coluim</i> ‘devotee of St Columba’. Columba was a 6th-century monk of Irish origin who played a leading part in the conversion to Christianity of Scotland and northern England;  see also  Callum   and   Colm .  He has always been one of the most popular saints in Scotland, but in the Middle Ages it was felt to be presumptuous to give the names of saints directly to children; instead their blessing was invoked by prefixing the name with <i>mael</i> ‘devotee of’ or <i>gille</i> ‘servant of’. Since the 1930s the given name has been used widely in the English-speaking world, not just by those with Scottish connections."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Malcolm Drummond 7th Thane of Lennox was born after 1209 as the son of Malcolm Beg Drummond 6th Thane of Lennox and Ada of Maldwin. He married Errick MacDhonnchad in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1278, in Drymen, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"Aft 1209–1278":"pärast 1209–1278","1209–1278":"1209–1278","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1237–1304":"1237–1304","1268–1305":"1268–1305","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1275–1375":"1275–1375","1250–1301":"1250–1301","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","about 1270":"umbes 1270","ABT 1268":"umbes 1268","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Aft 1209":"pärast 1209","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","1237":"1237","1301":"1301","1268":"1268","1278":"1278","1332":"1332","1200":"1200","1375":"1375","about 1275":"umbes 1275","1209":"1209","Drymen, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Drymen, Stirlingshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Aft 1209–1278":"1209 jälkeen–1278","1209–1278":"1209–1278","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1237–1304":"1237–1304","1268–1305":"1268–1305","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1275–1375":"1275–1375","1250–1301":"1250